title: Nice having you, Brüning.

The Agriculture Ministry, led by the respected Martin Schiele, does its best to defend the decree before Hindenburg—but to no avail.

In truth, policy disputes isn’t what will seal Brüning’s fate. Hindenburg had merely planned to give him a few more months to try his luck at Lausanne. But the scheming—and the sense of urgency—pushed by Schleicher, Meissner, and Oskar is forcing his hand toward an early, rash decision.